  <title>__callingconvention</title>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">__callingconvention</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="List">&lt;idConvention&gt;<tab />Specifies the calling convention for this entity. &#160;&lt;idConvention&gt; must be one of the following:</para>
    <list id="1" type="ul" listtype="bullet" formatstring="&#183;" format-charset="SYMBOL_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="List" style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;">
      <list id="1" level="1" type="ul" listtype="bullet" formatstring="&#111;" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="List" style="font-family:&apos;Courier New&apos;; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;">
        <li styleclass="List">CLIPPER</li>
        <li styleclass="List">STRICT</li>
        <li styleclass="List">PASCAL</li>
        <li styleclass="List">CALLBACK</li>
        <li styleclass="List">THISCALL</li>
      </list>
    </list>
    <para styleclass="List"><tab />Most calling conventions are for backward compatibility only. <br/>There are 2 exceptions:<br/>CLIPPER declares that a method has untyped parameters. This is usually only needed for methods without any declared parameters. Otherwise the compiler will assume CLIPPER calling convention when it detects untyped parameters. <br/>Methods and Functions in external DLL may have STRICT, PASCAL, CALLBACK</para>
    <para styleclass="List"></para>
  </body>
